{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"1e114f49-e773-4310-95c0-0cd9aa648390","content":"Here's what you need:\n\n## 1. Set shared properties via `Directory.Build.props` (at solution root)\n\n```xml\n<Project>\n  <PropertyGroup>\n    <!-- Switch from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform runner -->\n    <EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>\n    <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n\n    <!-- Let 'dotnet test' delegate to the new platform -->\n    <TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>\n  </PropertyGroup>\n</Project>\n```\n\n## 2. In each test `.csproj`\n\n- **Remove** the `Microsoft.NET.Test.Sdk` package reference (the MSTest runner replaces it).\n- **Add** the TRX report extension so CI logging keeps working:\n\n```xml\n<PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport\" Version=\"1.5.3\" />\n```\n\nYour existing `MSTest` (or `MSTest.TestFramework` + `MSTest.TestAdapter`) 3.8.0 references stay as-is — they already bundle the Microsoft.Testing.Platform.\n\n## 3. CI command\n\nNo change needed — `dotnet test --logger trx` continues to work because `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport` translates VSTest-style arguments for you.\n\n**Quick sanity check after migrating:** run `dotnet test` locally and confirm you see the Microsoft.Testing.Platform banner (e.g., `Microsoft(R) Testing Platform …`) instead of the old VSTest output.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b663d63e-1286-404b-980e-85936425143a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to migrate their MSTest 3.8.0 test projects from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform. Let me provide a clear, concise answer based on my knowledge of this migration path.\n\nKey changes needed:\n\n1. **Per-project or Directory.Build.props**: Set `<TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>` to enable `dotnet test` integration with the new platform.\n\n2. **MSTest 3.8.0** already includes Microsoft.Testing.Platform support - no package changes needed.\n\n3. **Enable the runner**: Set `<EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>` and `<OutputType>Exe</OutputType>`.\n\n\n4. **CI integration**: The `dotnet test` command continues to work, though you may need to adjust logger arguments depending on your .NET version—the `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport` property handles compatibility across .NET 8 and 9.\n\nFor the TRX logger output, I need to add the `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport` package since the Microsoft.Testing.Platform requires it explicitly. Let me reconsider the setup for a standard MSTest 3.8.0 project and outline what goes in **Directory.Build.props** to keep configuration consistent across all three test projects. For TRX logging with the new testing platform, I need to add the `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport` package and use `--report-trx` instead of the older `--logger trx` syntax. With MSTest 3.8.0, the setup involves enabling the MSTestRunner, setting the output type to Exe, and adding TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport for compatibility with `dotnet test`, plus adding the necessary NuGet reference.\n\nSince the user wants consistent property configuration across projects, I should recommend using a `Directory.Build.props` file to centralize these settings.","outputTokens":1455,"requestId":"1BC8:17551C:209BB50:23FAF82:6A03CE13"},"id":"dd7f37ed-ca32-4831-9a70-6add11447a40","timestamp":"2026-05-13T01:04:47.620Z","parentId":"b984220b-eb12-4d3e-8166-d00a92f53891"}
